tayschon@mehta.anu.edu.au (Sam Taylor) writes:

>Perhaps you could answer this - one question I've always had about
>the bandwidth of the OCS is:  

>	"How come 4 hi-res planes != 8 low-res planes??"

The OCS and ECS chips simply don't have the ability to handle
8 planes.  The time slots are available, but the chips can't use
them.

>Surely that means that OCS machines potentially have enough
>DMA slots to display 8 low-res plane images?

Yep - the slots are there, but the other registers needed to display
those two bitplanes don't exist.  If you were to make an ECS chipset
that would display 8 bitplanes, you would need to add two more sets
of bitplane pointer registers, modulo registers, and the like.  And
worse, you'd need to add *212* color registers. With the technology
available at the time the OCS/ECS chips were designed, this would have
been prohibitive, in both chip real estate and in cost.

