In article <93295.134321MBS110@psuvm.psu.edu>, Mark 'Mark' Sachs <MBS110@psuvm.psu.edu> writes:
> In the interests of torturing myself until the copy of Frontier I
> pre-ordered from Sideline Software arrives, I have a few questions
> for those who own it. Hope you can tear yourselves away long enough
> to answer... :)
> 
> 1. How big is the variety of ships you can purchase? That is -- are
> you limited to stereotypical little privateering ships, or could you
> purchase, say, a battleship?
> 
 The variety of ships you can buy is very large. Just about everything
 upto a space station can be purchased. I'm not sure but I don't think
 space stations can be bought.

> 2. Surface detail on planets. I know you can apparently fly anywhere
> you want on the surface (people talking about flying to London, and
> so forth.) What's surface detail like? I mean, it seems an onerous
> task to detail just the Earth (never mind 100 billion other planetary
> systems) as heavily as the city in the demo is. Are there basically
> large stretches of empty land and water with a few detailed areas, or
> what?
> 
   Most moons and planets have mountains and (random?) craters.
   A lot of famous objects in our solar system are modelled correctly.
   Hey, I just past under the Golden Gate bridge. Other highlights are
   mount Olympus on Mars, the sulphury (sp?) color of Io etc...

> 3. Is there daytime and nighttime on planets? What about weather?
> 
   Yes there is daytime and nighttime. This works great when you
   speed up time. As for weather, there are clouds.

> 4. Can you enter the atmosphere of gas giants?
> 
   Yes, I entered Saturns atmosphere once. you can hear wind noises,
   but don't go too deep or you'll explode (why not implode?)

> 5. Is the scenery frangible? (That is, can you blow up the buildings...)
> 
   Most of the buildings are not real. I.e. try flying through the
   domes and buildings at Ross. Not a scratch.

   Ofcourse the relevant scenery IS real. As many found out when they
   bumped into a space station.

> 6. What's the deal with "flying missions for a planet"? It sounds far
> more interesting than mere trading. Are these randomly generated missions,
> or pre-written, or what?
> 
  I think they are mostly random. They include transporting documents
  for the military, parcels or people. Usually there is a time constraint.
  I.e. if you don't get there in time you don't get paid :-(

  Getting there in time can be difficult. A hyperspace jump for any ship
  with any engine will always take a week for the maximum range of that
  ship/engine configuration.

  This means that a small ship can overtake a large one during hyperspace
  jumps. Since hyperspace gas cloud analyzers are dirt cheap, you can
  determine the destination of a big transporter, when it has jumped,
  then jump after him/her and arrive there first to prepare a warm 
  welcome... :-)

> 7. Is the scenery just there to look at (and crash into :) ) or does it
> serve any other purpose? Like, say, if you're looking for GENOM Incorporated
> and see a GENOM tower in the city ahead of you, you know that's really
> where they are.
> 
> Hmm... that'll do with a start. I just have to keep from drooling on the
> keyboard long enough to send this :)
> 
