I think so aswell... It seems to me that Frontier isn't really a game, it's
...how should I put it...it wants to get a Sense Of Wonder across to the
player, and the gaming obscures this. The solar system, for instance, is
correct to the smallest detail: the planets are of the correct size, on the
correct distance from the sun, with the correct gravity and correct lengths
of day and year. You can move around freely, and, for instance, watch Saturn
rising over Titan. You can do complicated space-faring maneuvres like using
planets gravity to increase your speed (slingshot). However, at the same time
you can go around killing pirates and gathering money, and you don't have
to bother about distractions such as multiple sunrises or slingshots. It
feels to me as if the 'game' part is just glued on top of things, as if the
programmer really just wanted to explore space, and threw in a bit of sex,
drugs, and rock'n roll to make it sell...

Frontier has the makings of a monumental game, of being 'the mother of
all games', but it's not ready. It'd have needed perhaps another year of
developing to iron out bugs and reconcile the gaming bit with the exploration
bit.

What's most needed, is better resistance (more big bad enemies -less
'flies'- and smarter and more accurate), more missions (REAL missions), and
the possibility to discover unexpected things when you leave the three human
realms.
Perhaps a few of the add-ons should be modified aswell... Shield generators
should be much bigger and more expensive, the docking computer could be
scrapped altogether... I'd like it if there were 'fleets' out there to
fight aswell, and the possibility of organising one oneself.

Anyway, the space-battle bit has to be redone pretty much from scratch.

Still, it's a great game until you reaches a certain level, no doubt about
that. I heard that Braben plans on releasing 'mission disks'... That might
do the trick.

