Argh...
The velocity vector is NOT "locked". It's just shown as relative to the
greatest mass around, usually the nearest star, or when you're very near
to a planet, to that.
When you're traveling several thousand kilometers per second relative to
the star of the system, you are NOT going be able to change the direction
not speed too much during one combat with even the 28G acceleration some
ships give.
However, if your velocity vector was shown relative to the opponent, it would
be much less, usually some hunderds or maybe thousands of kilometers per hour,
and changing constantly. Admitted, it would be nice if you could tell the
computer to show your speed relative to the target.
Remember, things are relative. The attacking ship more or less matches its
velocity with you, that is, you're both traveling at great speed towards
the system you happened to tell the autopilot to go to.
Just ignore the velocity indicators. They are of use only when going to an
orbit.
Speaking of orbits, if you're able to calculate the right velocity vector
to put you on a crossing orbit with the destination planet, you'll be able
to get there either with much less fuel consumption in the same time, or
much faster with the same fuel consumption (or anything in between), than
with the autopilot. In space, the straight line rarely is the fastest (or
shortest, calculated with delta v) route between two points.
