Right, I got Frontier on Thursday, not one of the bugfixed versions. (btw, if
someone can post a proggy to fix the bugs I'd be most grateful, and also some
code to kill multitasking before frontier starts, so I can play off my HD)

I currently have an Asp Explorer with 2 shield generators, Hyperspace Cloud Analyiser,
and all the other stuff.

Anyway, the best way to earn money is to remove as much as possible from the ship,
and just trade between Barnards Star and Sol, until you get a decent ship, that
can defend itself.

Basically, targetting a ship manually is nigh on impossible, especially if it's
small. It's much easier to point in roughly the right direction, and let the autopilot
line it up properly, then let rip with the guns.

As to the acuracy, I once ran out of fuel heading towards Mars, and ended up being
catapulted around the sun, and out into space. Very impresive (but rather annoying)

Also, I tried to visit this asteroidal body, very close to a red giant, in one of
these multiple star systems, (can't remember the name off hand), but because the
planet was so close to the star, and on the other side, I couldn't get to it, I
suspect because of the gravity of the star being so close. The ship was shaking
all over the place as the autopilot tried to move, and once I switched to manual
the ship started falling back towards the sun before the stabalisers cut in.

In conclusion, the best kind of ship to have is one which is fairly large, and
able to take hard knocks, if you want to fly a smaller ship, you really need to get
to a point where you can cope with the controls.

One last point, stop flaming Frontier because it's not like Elite. The galaxy is
acurate, and impressivly so. It may have been annoying, but after my encounter with 
deep space, I spent ages trying to get it to swing around a star nicely.

I just hope that there *are* aliens out in the furthest reaches, because it'd
be a great pity if there aren't any. Although I suppose if the scientists are to
be belived, finding another inhabited world that has developped space flight will
be very difficult.......

Richard.



