>BTW: Wouldn't it be better (faster) if the auto pilot turned your ship around 
>halfway to the target and used (the more powerful) rear thrusters to slow down?
>This would burn more fuel, but make your journey shorter (time).  

Yes it would. But the autopilot is stupid.
If you think about it, it wouldn't even burn more fuel. You get a fixed amount
of energy from one ton of fuel. This energy is turned to a pushing force by
the thrusters. F=ma <=> a=F/m means that the more force you have pushing a
gievn mass, the greater the acceleration is.
Now, the more powerful main thrusters burn fuel quicker, and push with a
greater force. This force accelerates (or decelerates) the ship quicker, so
you need less time to reach a given speed. This means that when decelerating,
will will stop quicker, ie. may start decelerating later. Now, you can spend
the time won with this either coasting alog, which will not take any fuel,
but you'll still reach your destination faster, or you can accelerate longer,
reaching higher maximum speed, and get there even more faster.

Since the Frontier simulates celestial mechanics quite correctly, there would
be one even more efficient way of moving around: orbits. You would need even
less fuel, and get there in the same or less time.
