 In all the comparisons made between Warhead and Frontier I have not
yet heard about the most obvious, and in my opinion, most important
aspects of this simulator - the flight control/orientation system.
 
 I have heard that Frontier follows a "Force = Mass x Acceleration"
equation similar to that of Warhead.
How do the two control systems compare?
 
Things I like about Warheads control system:
 
  Relative ease of use. (still requires practice)
Forward/reverse thrusters are represented by left/right mouse buttons.
(the main thrusters vs the retrothrust performance ratio is 6.3g to 1g.)
 
General ship orientation is accomplished via the mouse - although I
much prefer a trackball for this.
 
  Warhead offers manual in addition to auto control of all the following
attitude functions:
 
1. One keypress auto-orients your ship's nose towards the direction of
   motion.
 
2. One keypress auto-orients your ship's nose opposite to your direction
   of motion. (facing rearward)
 
3. One keypress stops your ship automatically via the retro thrusters -
   or if necessary, during high velocity, it about-faces your ship and
   fires the main thrusters to execute a full stop of your momentum.
 
4. One keypress locks your nose onto a designated target, whether your
   moving or not.(I have heard inferences that Frontier has this feature)
 
5. Fine positioning option.
   Inertial dampers are available at a keypress (if you're having REAL
   trouble with drift).  This doubles as an inertialess flight option.
 
6. Auto Fly & Halt.
   This key flys you close to a designated target and parks you there.
   (the ability to preset the distance from target would have been a plus)
 
7. One other really helpful feature is the way the HUD system graphically
   depicts your relative speed/orientation and trajectory. As you travel,
   intially green colored dots on the HUD appear to move towards, across
   or receed into the distance (depending upon your ships orientation).
   As your speed increased in magnitude the dots shifted to blue, then
   on towards red when entering maximum velocity range.
 
 
 IMHO the above are not features but integral ingredients required for a
TRULY effective and intuitive spacecraft orientation/control system.
 
 Warhead has it's bugs, and it does lack the open endedness of ELITE wich
I still dearly love, but it sets a HUGE precedent in my book insofaras
the nav/control system that it utilizes.
 
Is Frontier's control system the be-all-end-all? No room for improvement?
Any Warheader/Frontierman care to indulge in a point by point comparison?
 
I'd like to know if and how the two sims differ in these respects.
 
 An aspect of the original ELITE that impressed me was it's easy to
use/understand point & click intuition interface as well as it's multi
in cockpit views - does Frontier still remain faithful to these tried and
tested conventions?
 
Detail level vs cockpit window size:
 I've read a lot about detail settings in Frontier, but nowhere do I hear
about an option to adjust the size of the 3D action window - after all
the original ELITE had a window size about 4X3"(?) and was VERY playable.
This would open the game up to a potentialy larger market share as well
as speed the game up considerably for many people. (ref. A-10 by Dynamix)  
 
 
